{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Channelizer\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Set MIDI channel to all MIDI messages Useful for routing MIDI messages to a specific channel It doesnt' modify midi events which are not channel specific\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Delay Pan\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Panner which also simulates the time delay associated to movement of a sound source in space No doppler effect when moving parameters, bc my knowledge of jsfx is rudimentary\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 x/y Pad\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Simple sliders that can be moved by clicking and dragging on an x/y pad It also outputs an audio signal accordingly, if you find a way to control things at audio rate (low pass filter is recommended in this case)\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Autotel Basic JSFX utils\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 JSFX utilities I've created for myself, when I've seen the need.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Channelizer\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Set the channel to all incoming midi, only if the signal is channel-specific.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Delay-pan\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Pan the audio signal, also delaying it slightly as to simulate the time sound takes to travel a distance. Speed of sound and stereo distance can be adjusted. It's not enough as HRTF, but the effect is still satisfying. For HRTF there are several really good plugins such as IEM suite.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 X/Y PAd\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Control stuff with a x/y pad - the idea is that you map your fx or synth params to either of the three sliders, and then control those by using x/y pad.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The utility also outputs an audio signal with the level, if you want to get experimental. I recommend disconnecting all it's outputs from the chain otherwise.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Installation\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Using reapack: Add to ReaPack by importing https://github.com/autotel/jsfx/raw/master/index.xml\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Without reapack:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Locate the JSFX folder on your reaper isntallation (one way to do this is to edit a js text file, 'save as' and instead of saving, copy the url where the current text file is located)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Download the text files and locate them on the correct folders.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Alternatively, you could try using the https://github.com/JoepVanlier/ysfx jsfx host\sa180\par}
}
